"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844118","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-23","<p>The Department is aware of delays and denials of entry of items into Gaza. The UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) is not currently consolidating data on these delays. We have requested UN OCHA to establish a mechanism for the collection of this data. DFID enables reconstruction efforts in Gaza through our support to the Materials Monitoring Unit of the Gaza Reconstruction Mechanism to monitor the import, storage, supply and use of construction materials. We welcome recent Israeli announcements to ease restrictions on the importation of material into Gaza for much needed infrastructure projects such as the proposed Central Gaza Desalination Plant and other waste water plants under construction, which many international donors are supporting.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-23T13:58:34.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844118/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844118/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-19","Gaza: Borders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent estimate she has made of the number of humanitarian and development items that have been delayed in entering or denied entry to Gaza by the Israeli authorities in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","128458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844119","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-26","<p>The average annual running cost for a Type 23 Frigate and a Type 45 Destroyer is approximately £11 million and £13.5 million respectively. These figures have been rounded to the nearest £100,000. The Type 31e programme is in its pre-procurement phase and it is therefore premature to provide an estimate of running costs.</p><p>The costs given include those items that are directly attributable to the ship, such as personnel costs, fuel and port visits and do not include such items as maintenance, training and generation costs.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","128460 ; 128462","2018-02-26T16:27:31.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844119/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844119/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Type 23 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average annual running cost is of a Type 23 frigate.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","128459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844120","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-26","<p>The average annual running cost for a Type 23 Frigate and a Type 45 Destroyer is approximately £11 million and £13.5 million respectively. These figures have been rounded to the nearest £100,000. The Type 31e programme is in its pre-procurement phase and it is therefore premature to provide an estimate of running costs.</p><p>The costs given include those items that are directly attributable to the ship, such as personnel costs, fuel and port visits and do not include such items as maintenance, training and generation costs.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","128459 ; 128462","2018-02-26T16:27:31.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844120/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844120/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Type 45 Destroyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the average annual running cost is of a Type 45 destroyer.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","128460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844121","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-09","<p>There is a standard service level agreement for contracted-out occupational health services provided on behalf of Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service. The service levels are strict and high to make sure value for money is achieved for the taxpayer. This includes tighter turnaround times for the delivery of occupational health services and financial penalties for poor performance.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-09T10:17:44.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844121/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844121/answer","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844121/answer/previousversion/43705","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-19","Prison and Probation Service: Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether there is a standard service level agreement for contracted-out occupational health services provided on behalf of Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","128461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844122","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-26","<p>The average annual running cost for a Type 23 Frigate and a Type 45 Destroyer is approximately £11 million and £13.5 million respectively. These figures have been rounded to the nearest £100,000. The Type 31e programme is in its pre-procurement phase and it is therefore premature to provide an estimate of running costs.</p><p>The costs given include those items that are directly attributable to the ship, such as personnel costs, fuel and port visits and do not include such items as maintenance, training and generation costs.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb","128459 ; 128460","2018-02-26T16:27:30.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844122/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844122/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-19","Type 31 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the estimated average annual running cost is of a Type 31e frigate.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","128462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844123","House of Commons Commission","false","2018-02-23","<p>Following recommendations made to all public sector bodies in the Environmental Audit Committee’s Report, <em>‘Plastic Bottles: Turning back the plastic tide’</em>, the House Service is currently reviewing the sustainability and environmental management of single use disposable plastics in the House of Commons.</p><p>A paper is to be submitted for discussion at the Administration Committee in March 2018 outlining the initiatives that can be taken forward to reduce the consumption of single use disposable plastics on the estate and increase recycling rates of all waste materials. I will ensure that the hon. Member’s suggestion is conveyed to the Committee.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2018-02-23T13:05:27.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844123/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844123/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2018-02-19","Parliamentary Estate: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, if the Commission will introduce a charge of 25p for disposable cups on the parliamentary estate; what assessment the Commission has made of the potential merits of the recommendations made in the reports of the Environmental Audit Committee on plastic bottles and coffee cups, HC339 and HC 657, published on 22 December 2017 and 5 January 2018 respectively; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","128463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844124","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-27","<p>There was a standard service level agreement for contracted-out occupational health services for HM Prison and Probation Service in July 2017. However, the new occupational health services contract, which came in to effect in October 2017, has stricter and more stringent service levels.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-27T16:36:53.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844124/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844124/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-19","Prison and Probation Service: Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether there was a standard service level agreement for contracted out occupational health services on behalf of HM Prison and Probation Service at the time those services were contracted out to a third party service provider in July 2017.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","128464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844125","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-27","<p>The new standard service level agreement - with supplier OH Assist - for contracted out Occupational Health services for Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service has the flexibility for the introduction of future variations at any point during its four year duration, depending on operational need and in line with Public Contract Regulations.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Secretary of State’s strategy for prison reform, new freedoms have been afforded to Governors that enable prisons to leave national contracts, like the OH Assist Occupational Health Services contract, in order to make their own local arrangements.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-02-27T16:36:26.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844125/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844125/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-19","Prison and Probation Service: Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he has plans to introduce variations in the standard service level agreement for contracted out services for Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service Occupational Health service.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","128465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844126","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not have any contractual relationship with the third-party service provider HML and no cases have been transferred.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-02-27T17:52:56.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844126/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844126/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-19","Ministry of Justice: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many open cases were transferred to the third party service provider HML when that company's contract started July 2017.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","128466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844127","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-09","<p>4 October 2017 was the date when the new occupational health services contract standard service level agreement for Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service came in to effect with OH Assist.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-09T10:19:04.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844127/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844127/answer","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844127/answer/previousversion/43691","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-19","Prison and Probation Service: Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what date will standard service level agreements for occupational health services for personnel of Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service come into effect with its third party service provider.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","128467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844128","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>Local authorities may incur more expenditure than they have budgeted for, which is why they are required to maintain a level of unallocated reserve commensurate with sound financial risk management. However, recognising the pressures on local services and impact of inflation, the Local Government Finance Settlement provided all councils with the ability to increase their council tax by an additional one per cent, without a local referendum. This strikes the right balance between allowing local authorities to make tough decisions to address service pressures, and protecting council tax-payers from excessive bill rises.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-02-22T17:39:24.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844128/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844128/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-19","Social Services: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether he will make available additional funding for Sheffield children's services to tackle that local authority's overspend in 2017-2018.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","128468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844129","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-22","<p>In Gaza, the UK has provided £1.9 million to the UN Children’s Fund (UNICEF) to support approximately 1 million Gazans by providing clean water, rehabilitating sanitation facilities and promoting hygiene standards to stop the spread of disease. Additionally, the UK is a long-term supporter of the UN Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA), which provides basic services to 1.3 million people in Gaza. In 2017/18 we have so far provided around £50 million to UNRWA across the region.</p><p> </p><p>The European Union (EU) is currently supporting six development projects in Gaza through multilateral bodies including UNICEF and UNRWA, totalling over €58 million. The EU is also supporting a number of humanitarian projects in Gaza. The UK’s financing share of EU expenditure varies year on year but has been approximately 15%.</p><p> </p><p>The UK also provides core un-earmarked contributions to multilateral bodies such as UNICEF and the International Committee of the Red Cross and is a shareholder in a number of major international financial institutions, such as the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development and the European Investment Bank, which are working across the West Bank and Gaza.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-22T17:04:21.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844129/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844129/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-19","Gaza: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, which multilateral projects in the Gaza Strip her Department helps fund; and how much is disbursed from the public purse for each such project.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","128469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844130","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Government is committed to promoting fairness and transparency for leaseholders.</p><p>On 21 December 2017, the Government set out a package of measures to tackle abuses and unfair practices in the leasehold market. This includes introducing legislation to prohibit the development of new build leasehold houses, other than in exceptional circumstances; restricting ground rents in newly established leases of houses and flats to a peppercorn (zero financial value), and working with the Law Commission to support existing leaseholders which includes making buying a freehold or extending a lease easier, faster, fairer and cheaper.</p><p>A number of developers have introduced schemes to compensate existing leaseholders affected by onerous ground rents, but these must go further and faster. The Government wants to see this support extended to all those with onerous ground rents, including second hand buyers, and for customers to be proactively contacted. The then Housing Minister wrote to developers on 21 December 2017 to set out this position. We will be keeping a close eye on progress and will consider measures that could be pursued to take action if necessary.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-02-27T16:22:27.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844130/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/844130/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-19","Leasehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what progress his Department has made on its proposals for leasehold reform for people currently living in leasehold properties.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","128470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838866","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government has made clear that the UK is leaving the Customs Union. By leaving the Customs Union and establishing a new and ambitious customs arrangement with the EU, we will be able to forge new trade relationships with our partners around the world, and maintain as frictionless trade as possible in goods between the UK and EU, providing a positive and powerful voice for free trade.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-02-20T17:18:42.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838866/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838866/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838866/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-02-08","Customs Unions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the benefits and possibility of time-limited extensions on key parts of the EU customs union once the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL5506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838867","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-22","<p>It is the Government’s intention that the administration of the VAT regime following EU exit will remain largely as it currently is, as far as is desirable and practicable. Further information can be found in the Impact Assessment that accompanied the Taxation (Cross Border Trade) Bill, published on 20/11/2017.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2018-02-22T15:19:48.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838867/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838867/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-08","VAT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact of leaving the EU VAT area on British companies, including small and micro businesses.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL5507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838868","Department for International Trade","false","2018-02-22","<p>The UK is talking to a number of countries about future trading options, and it is too early to say what this will mean in a particular case or with any particular country.</p><p>As one of the world's largest economies, we have the chance to work with old and new partners to build a truly Global Britain at the heart of international trade.</p><p>We are using instruments like Joint Trade Reviews, a collaborative in-depth analysis into the mutual trading relationship between the UK and a partner country, to look for areas we can improve our bilateral trading relationships.</p><p>We will aim, through these discussions, to put in place various mechanisms to improve trading relations and remove barriers affecting UK businesses.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2018-02-22T17:39:16.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838868/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838868/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838868/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-02-08","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the ability of the UK to make sector-specific trade agreements with other nations in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a trade deal and reverts to World Trade Organisation rules.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL5508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838869","Women and Equalities","false","2018-02-20","<p>In 2017, the FTSE 100 had 25.2% women in executive committees and direct reports. This had barely changed from 2016, showing that robust action is needed from businesses to achieve the Hampton-Alexander Review’s target of 33% by 2020.</p><p>To increase the level of ambition, the Hampton-Alexander Review has now extended the executive pipeline target of 33% women from the FTSE 100 to the wider FTSE 350 – around 1 in 2 of all new appointments needing to go to women to achieve this target by 2020. We will continue to support the Review to work collaboratively with business to disseminate the importance of diversity in executive roles.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2018-02-20T14:14:31.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838869/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838869/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838869/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2018-02-08","Females: Directors","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of progress towards the target of at least 33 per cent representation of women on the combined executive committee and direct reports to the executive committee in all FTSE100 companies by 2020.","false","Biography information for Lord Allen of Kensington",,"Lord Allen of Kensington","HL5509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838870","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-02-20","<p>Prison capacity is defined using the terms Certified Normal Accommodation (CNA) and Operational Capacity. These terms are defined separately as:</p><p> </p><ul><li>CNA, or uncrowded capacity, is the Prison Service’s own measure of accommodation. CNA represents the good, decent standard of accommodation that Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service aspires to provide all prisoners; and</li></ul><p> </p><ul><li>the Operational Capacity of a prison is the total number of prisoners that an establishment can hold taking into account control, security and the proper operation of the planned regime. It is determined by Prison Group Directors on the basis of operational judgement and experience.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The total prison population is in excess of CNA however this total is always below the total operational capacity of the estate.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2018-02-20T17:33:58.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838870/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838870/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838870/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-08","Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the reply by Lord Keen of Elie on 8 February, what the “certified capacity of the prison population” refers to; and whether the prison population has exceeded the Certified Normal Accommodation of the prison system at any time over the last 20 years.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL5510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838871","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-20","<p>These figures are not held by the department.</p><p>There are restrictions on selling on a property bought under Right to Buy within five years and under our reinvigorated scheme every additional home sold off must be replaced by an additional one, nationally. Local authorities should deliver these additional affordable homes within three years.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2018-02-20T17:20:45.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838871/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838871/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838871/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-08","Council Housing: Sales","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the percentage of former council housing now owned by private landlords, for each local housing authority in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL5511"
