"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839215","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-23","<p>The Domestic Partnership Act will withdraw the entitlement for same sex couples to marry and replace it with a provision for domestic partnerships for all couples, regardless of gender. Same sex couples entering into a 'domestic partnership' will be entitled to the same benefits as married couples. Those who have been legally married in Bermuda since the Supreme Court decision in May 2017, will retain their married status and have the same legal rights as those in domestic partnerships. The Supreme Court ruling permitted same sex couples in Bermuda to marry, but it did not address the entitlement of same sex couples to the same benefits as opposite sex married couples. The Act now put those rights on a clear statutory footing. Less than a year ago, same sex couples had no legal recognition at all under Bermudian law.</p><p>The Minister for the Commonwealth and the UN raised the issue of human rights including LGBT rights and the need to ensure that our collective human rights obligations are upheld, in his meeting with the Bermuda Premier in October 2017, and at the Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council in November 2017.</p><p>Officials have engaged on a regular basis with the Government of Bermuda, and with all of the Overseas Territories to encourage and promote LGBT equality.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","127775","2018-02-23T14:39:59.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839215/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839215/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","Bermuda: LGBT People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment his Department has made of the status of  LGBT+ rights in Bermuda.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","127771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839216","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>Detainee welfare concerns in Immigration Removal Centres can be raised at any point, to the Home Office, NHS (England) or the custodial supplier as appropriate. The BBC first made the Home Office aware of the specific issues later aired by Panorama on 24 August 2017. The Government takes the health and welfare of immigration detainees very seriously and expects the highest standards from those who manage the detention estate on its behalf.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T11:13:47.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839216/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839216/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Brook House Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when her Department first become aware of detainee welfare concerns at Brook House Immigration Removal Centre.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","127772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839217","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government made an immediate assessment that G4S needed to take swift action against an agreed action plan to address necessary improvements at Brook House Immigration Removal Centre. These improvements will ensure that the standards of detainee welfare expected by the Government are met. Progress against this plan is being closely monitored.</p><p>Stephen Shaw is currently assessing progress against the recommendations in his report into the Welfare in Detention of Vulnerable Persons published in January 2016. In addition, the G4S Board has commissioned an independent review to establish the factors affecting staff morale and behaviour and attitudes to whistleblowing. Neither independent review has reported yet. The Government will consider their findings very carefully in due course.</p><p>Independent scrutiny is a vital part of assurance that our removal centres are secure and humane. The Government will continue to implement action in response to independent recommendations made by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Prisons and by the centre’s Independent Monitoring Board.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T11:14:00.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839217/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839217/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Brook House Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of what led to concerns about detainee welfare at Brook House Immigration Removal Centre.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","127773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839218","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>This information is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:21:09.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839218/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839218/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people who are (a) survivors of sexual and gender-based violence and (b) otherwise recognised as vulnerable under the Adults at Risk policy have been brought to immigration detention centres since 12 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","127774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839219","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-23","<p>The Domestic Partnership Act will withdraw the entitlement for same sex couples to marry and replace it with a provision for domestic partnerships for all couples, regardless of gender. Same sex couples entering into a 'domestic partnership' will be entitled to the same benefits as married couples. Those who have been legally married in Bermuda since the Supreme Court decision in May 2017, will retain their married status and have the same legal rights as those in domestic partnerships. The Supreme Court ruling permitted same sex couples in Bermuda to marry, but it did not address the entitlement of same sex couples to the same benefits as opposite sex married couples. The Act now put those rights on a clear statutory footing. Less than a year ago, same sex couples had no legal recognition at all under Bermudian law.</p><p>The Minister for the Commonwealth and the UN raised the issue of human rights including LGBT rights and the need to ensure that our collective human rights obligations are upheld, in his meeting with the Bermuda Premier in October 2017, and at the Overseas Territories Joint Ministerial Council in November 2017.</p><p>Officials have engaged on a regular basis with the Government of Bermuda, and with all of the Overseas Territories to encourage and promote LGBT equality.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan","127771","2018-02-23T14:39:59.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839219/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839219/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","Bermuda: Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Bermudian counterpart on same-sex marriage legislation.","