"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839220","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-22","<p>The information requested is not centrally collected in this format.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-22T14:52:45.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839220/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839220/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Mental Health Services: Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the number of asylum seekers who received therapy or counselling from the NHS during 2017.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839221","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>Monitoring of the financial performance of strategic suppliers is commercially sensitive information and is not therefore published.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-02-20T12:00:09.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839221/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839221/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Home Office: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2018 to Question 123744, on Home Office: Contracts, if her Department will publish its monitoring of the financial performance of strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","127777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839222","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Home Office does not publish data relating to the number of cases where a decision has been made after 6 months, however, the data on the number of cases awaiting decision for more than 6 months can be found on the tab ASY 11 in the link below;</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-november-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/asylum-transparency-data-november-2017</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:00:53.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839222/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839222/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum applications have been open for a period of two years or longer prior to 6 February 2018.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839223","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>As set out in the previous answer, the Department reviews allowed appeals in order to learn lessons. It should be noted that in many cases new evidence is often submitted at an appeal hearing, which was not available when the original decision was made. In addition to the Department’s own direct assurance, the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration also has a key role in looking the quality of departmental processes.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:24:41.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839223/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839223/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 15 January 2018 to Question 121751, what steps her Department plans to take to monitor the effectiveness of those arrangements.","false","Biography information for Afzal Khan","Manchester, Gorton","Afzal Khan","127779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839224","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government does not return refugees to Sudan since such persons have been found to require international protection.</p><p>Sudanese nationals who have, however, been found not to need protection and have no right to remain are expected to leave the UK. If they do not leave voluntarily we may seek to enforce their return on case-by-case basis, when it is safe to do so. We do not routinely monitor the treatment of individuals once removed from the UK. They are, by definition, foreign nationals who have been found not to need protection and it would be inappropriate for us to assume any ongoing responsibility for them when they return to their country.</p><p>Should the Home Office receive specific allegations that a returnee has experienced ill-treatment on return, it would be investigated in partnership with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p><p>There are no plans to put in place asylum seeker returns and readmission arrangements for Sudan.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","127788","2018-02-20T12:11:33.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839224/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839224/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Deportation: Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government plans to carry out post-removal monitoring of refugees sent back to Sudan to (a) ensure their safety and (b) collect data on any adverse consequences for them of their return.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839225","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-20","<p>The department continues to provide an exception payment service for benefit recipients. Citibank is currently the contractor for that service and is being replaced by i-movo. All current simple payment recipients will move to the i-movo service by the end of March 2018.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-02-20T12:27:08.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839225/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839225/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-08","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons her Department removed the simple payment method in March 2018 for benefit claimants without a bank account.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839226","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-20","<p>The simple payment service is being replaced by a new payment service. Customers can still receive payment at a PayPoint outlet but payment will be limited to £100 per transaction. Customers with higher than £100 entitlement can make multiple transactions at the same PayPoint outlet on the same day, subject to funds available from that outlet. The Department continues to encourage and support benefit customers, where possible, to receive payment via a bank, building society or a credit union account which does not have a similar restriction.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-02-20T12:34:38.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839226/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839226/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-08","Universal Credit: Voucher Schemes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the reasons were for the decision that the voucher scheme would give universal credit claimants £100 a time rather than the monthly paid benefit payable under the simple payment method.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839227","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-22","<p>Public Health England, with the support of NHS England, published guidance last year, ‘Better care for people with co-occurring mental health and alcohol/drug use conditions: A guide for commissioners and service providers’. This guidance is designed to help ensure people who have co-occurring problems with mental health and drug use are not excluded from services. In the guidance, commissioners and service providers are encouraged to work together to improve access to services which can reduce harm, improve health, enhance recovery, enable services to respond effectively and flexibly and prevent exclusion. The document is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/625809/Co-occurring_mental_health_and_alcohol_drug_use_conditions.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/625809/Co-occurring_mental_health_and_alcohol_drug_use_conditions.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>In addition, a national Commissioning for Quality and Innovation scheme to help prevent ill health by risky behaviours, offers an opportunity for inpatients in mental health services, who drink at or above established risk levels, to be supported with an appropriate evidence-based intervention. The scheme is intended to complement and reinforce existing activity to reduce alcohol harm in this population. Further information is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/cquin-indicator-specification/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/cquin-indicator-specification/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-02-22T14:49:42.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839227/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839227/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Mental Health Services: Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to reduce drink and drug abuse among mental health service users.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839228","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-26","<p>The 2016 UK Chief Medical Officers’ low risk drinking guidelines provide the public with the most up to date scientific information to help people make informed decisions about their own drinking. The guidelines recommend that if you are pregnant or think you could become pregnant, the safest approach is not to drink alcohol at all to keep risks to the baby to a minimum. The guidelines are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/alcohol-consumption-advice-on-low-risk-drinking" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/alcohol-consumption-advice-on-low-risk-drinking</a></p><p>Advice about alcohol and drugs is available to pregnant women as part of their routine antenatal care. Pregnant women who misuse alcohol or drugs will be put in contact with a midwife or doctor who has special experience in the care of pregnant women with alcohol or drug problems. They will be able to refer them to an alcohol or drug treatment programme and other organisations that can help.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-26T17:10:17.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839228/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839228/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Pregnancy: Alcoholic Drinks and Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the incidence of drink and drug abuse among pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839229","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that children and young people stay safe online. The Department’s ‘Keeping children safe in education’ statutory guidance states that schools should ensure children are taught about safeguarding, includes staying safe online.</p><p> </p><p>E-safety is covered at all Key Stages in the national curriculum for computing. It is compulsory in maintained schools and can be used as a benchmark by academies and free schools. The content was developed with input from e-safety experts including Childnet, NSPCC and the UK Safer Internet Centre. The introduction of e-safety content at Key Stage 1 reflects the fact that children are increasingly using the internet and social media from a young age.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working closely with the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on any additional content on online safety that may be taught through the new subjects of Relationships Education and Relationships and Sex Education and potentially through compulsory Personal, Social, Health and Economic education.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Council for Child Internet Safety recently published 'Education for a Connected World framework'. This Framework supports one of the key aims of the Government’s Internet Safety Strategy of supporting children to stay safe and make a positive contribution online. It includes a section on privacy and security.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-20T15:24:18.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839229/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839229/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Students: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps are being taken to ensure that students are educated on issues of privacy and personal security on social media.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839230","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>Information on asylum claimants is held on both the asylum case file and the main immigration database. This will include personal details of claimants and relatives such as claimed dates and places of birth, claimed religion, claimed ethnicity, as well as details of their asylum claims. The way this information is stored is such that it is often not possible to report on these information fields without conducting a manual search of both paper and electronic records. Therefore, we cannot identify how many asylum claims have been granted or refused leave from specific ethnicities or parts of the countries of origin.</p><p> </p><p>Published data relating to the outcomes of asylum claims from each country (including Sudan) can be found in tab as_01 at volume 1 of the quarterly Immigration Statistics release:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2017-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2017-data-tables</a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:40:33.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839230/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839230/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Asylum: Darfur","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department holds on the number of non-Arab Darfuri asylum seekers who had their asylum claims rejected in 2017.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839231","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-26","<p>All asylum and human rights claims from Sudanese nationals are carefully considered on their individual merits, and in accordance with our obligations under the Refugee Convention and European Convention on Human Rights. Those who have been found not to need protection are refused have a right of appeal to the independent courts.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-02-26T17:08:45.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839231/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839231/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","Sudan: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made an assessment of the danger to non-Arab Dafuris sent to Khartoum after having their asylum claims rejected in the UK.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839233","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government does not return refugees to Sudan since such persons have been found to require international protection.</p><p>Sudanese nationals who have, however, been found not to need protection and have no right to remain are expected to leave the UK. If they do not leave voluntarily we may seek to enforce their return on case-by-case basis, when it is safe to do so. We do not routinely monitor the treatment of individuals once removed from the UK. They are, by definition, foreign nationals who have been found not to need protection and it would be inappropriate for us to assume any ongoing responsibility for them when they return to their country.</p><p>Should the Home Office receive specific allegations that a returnee has experienced ill-treatment on return, it would be investigated in partnership with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office.</p><p>There are no plans to put in place asylum seeker returns and readmission arrangements for Sudan.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","127780","2018-02-20T12:11:33.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839233/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839233/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Asylum: Sudan","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government is in the process of drafting asylum seeker returns and readmission arrangements for Sudan.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839234","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-22","<p>There has not yet been any high volume hydraulic fracturing, or ‘fracking’, at the site in Yorkshire, and none is permitted to take place in the Humber. The water environment around the Yorkshire site is being monitored which is required to be assessed in accordance with the environmental permit, before, during and after fracking.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy made a written statement on 25 January regarding progress on the consent for fracking in Yorkshire.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-22T15:26:57.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839234/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839234/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-02-08","Fracking: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent assessment has been made of whether there has been any water contamination as a result of fracking in Yorkshire and the Humber.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839235","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Be Clear on Cancer campaigns are designed to raise the public’s awareness of specific cancer symptoms, encourage people with those symptoms to go to the doctor and diagnose cancer at an earlier stage. Public Health England ran a Be Clear on Cancer Skin Cancer campaign in Devon, Cornwall and Somerset in 2014. The Be Clear on Cancer Skin Cancer materials are freely available online via the Campaign Resource Centre at:</p><p><a href="https://campaignresources.phe.gov.uk/resources" target="_blank">https://campaignresources.phe.gov.uk/resources</a></p><p>The decision on which cancers should be the focus of Be Clear on Cancer campaigns is informed by a steering group, whose members include primary and secondary care clinicians, and key voluntary sector organisations. This is under constant review, informed by the available data and medical information resources.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-20T17:13:14.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839235/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839235/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839235/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Skin Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to raise awareness of services to check people for skin cancer.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839236","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>The employment rate in Yorkshire and the Humber has grown by 4.1 percentage points since March 2010 to 73%. Our ambitious Industrial Strategy will build on this by enabling the UK to work more productively and boost the earning power of people, businesses, places and the nation as a whole. The Government is backing the Industrial Strategy in Yorkshire and the Humber by investing £1.3bn in local growth funding to create jobs, improve skill levels, and help raise living standards. In addition we agreed a significant programme of Enterprise Zones, which are already attracting investment and jobs across the area.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-20T13:59:33.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839236/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839236/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839236/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Average Earnings: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to improve the level of average weekly earnings in Yorkshire and Humber.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","127791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839237","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Government has standing instructions to all diplomatic staff to follow the revised December 2013 guidelines on interactions with tobacco companies. The Government does not catalogue the representations it makes on behalf of companies.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-02-22T17:55:11.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839237/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839237/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839237/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how his Department monitors the observance of guidance on support to the tobacco industry in its overseas posts; what assessment he has made of compliance with that guidance by those posts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","127792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839239","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Government does not catalogue the representations it makes on behalf of companies. The Government has standing instructions to all diplomatic staff to follow the revised December 2013 guidelines on interactions with tobacco companies. In line with this guidance, however,some assistance may be offered to counter discriminatory practices.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-02-22T17:58:30.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839239/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839239/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839239/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will set out all instances where assistance was provided to the tobacco industry by UK overseas posts since December 2013.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","127793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839240","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The attached table shows the number and percentage of pupils who were eligible for free school meals in (a) Ashfield constituency, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) England and went on to sustained education, employment or training destinations after completing Key Stage 4 in academic years 2013-14, 2014-15 and 2015-16 (the last three years for which data is available).</p><p>Information on pupil destinations is published annually, available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-destinations" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-destinations</a>.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-20T13:14:40.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839240/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839240/answer","127794 - Pupils with sustained education, employment or training destinations after key stage 4.docx","Pupils with sustained EET after key stage 4","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839240/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Young People: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what percentage of young people who were eligible for free school meals in (a) Ashfield constituency, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) England were in education, employment or training after completing Key Stage 4 in each of the last three years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","127794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839241","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-21","<p>The United Kingdom Government and UK officials overseas are committed to limiting interactions with the tobacco industry as part of Her Majesty’s Government’s obligations under the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has standing instructions to all diplomatic staff to follow the revised December 2013 guidelines on interactions with tobacco companies. In line with this guidance, assistance may be offered to counter discriminatory practices. The Government does not catalogue the representations it makes on behalf of companies.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","127796","2018-02-21T10:50:29.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839241/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839241/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how he monitors observance by UK overseas posts of the revised guidance on support to the tobacco industry published in December 2013.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","127795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839242","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-21","<p>The United Kingdom Government and UK officials overseas are committed to limiting interactions with the tobacco industry as part of Her Majesty’s Government’s obligations under the Framework Convention on Tobacco Control.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has standing instructions to all diplomatic staff to follow the revised December 2013 guidelines on interactions with tobacco companies. In line with this guidance, assistance may be offered to counter discriminatory practices. The Government does not catalogue the representations it makes on behalf of companies.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","127795","2018-02-21T10:50:29.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839242/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839242/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he has taken to monitor adherence to the revised guidance to UK overseas posts on support to the tobacco industry, issued in December 2013, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","127796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839243","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Department’s official estimates of Level 2 and 3 attainment by young people aged 19 are published annually. The latest figures available were published in March 2017 and the latest cohort for which attainment at age 19 is available is those aged 19 in 2016. The latest publication can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/level-2-and-3-attainment-by-young-people-aged-19-in-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/level-2-and-3-attainment-by-young-people-aged-19-in-2016</a>. It includes both national and local authority estimates by free school meal eligibility.</p><p> </p><p>A young person achieving two or more A levels or equivalent is classed as having achieved a full Level 3.</p><p> </p><p>Constituency figures are not included in the publication but are given in the table below. The constituency has been allocated based on the postcode of the young person’s residence at age 15. The local authority figure for Nottinghamshire has also been allocated based on the postcode of residence. This differs slightly to the methodology used in the local authority tables in the referenced publication which is based on the school location at age 15; however figures at local authority level are broadly similar.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Proportion of cohort 19 achieving full level 3</strong></p></td><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>Nottinghamshire</p></td><td><p>Ashfield Constituency</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>in 2014</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>35.7%</p></td><td><p>23.4%</p></td><td><p>18.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those not eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>60.5%</p></td><td><p>55.8%</p></td><td><p>43.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>57.0%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>52.5%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>40.2%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>in 2015</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>36.4%</p></td><td><p>22.8%</p></td><td><p>16.1%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those not eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>61.0%</p></td><td><p>55.2%</p></td><td><p>42.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>57.5%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>51.7%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>38.1%</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>in 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>36.2%</p></td><td><p>26.7%</p></td><td><p>23.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of those not eligible for FSM</p></td><td><p>60.7%</p></td><td><p>56.9%</p></td><td><p>42.2%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>All</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>57.1%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>53.3%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>39.3%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em><sup>1</sup></em><em>: Local authority and constituency are based on young person’s home postcode at age 15</em></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-20T13:49:21.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839243/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839243/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","GCE A-level: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of young people in (a) Ashfield, constituency, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) England who were eligible for free school meals at age 15 achieved two or more A levels or equivalent qualifications by the age of 19 in each of the last three years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","127797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839244","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-20","<p>Personal Independence Payment (PIP) is available to claimants whether they are in or out of work and it does not test fitness or capacity to work. Claimants who are terminally ill and who have a life expectancy of less than six months have their claims fast tracked and are automatically entitled to the enhanced rate of the PIP daily living component. Information on the number of people receiving PIP, whether they are terminally ill or not and the rates received, is available using Stat-Xplore: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-02-20T11:49:50.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839244/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839244/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-08","Personal Independence Payment: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many terminally ill personal independence payment claimants were assessed as fit to work; and how many and what proportion of those claimants were considered as ineligible for the enhanced daily rate in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","127798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839245","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The department publishes information on the percentage of 15 year old pupils from state-funded and special schools by free school meal status who entered higher education (HE) by age 19 by local authority and region.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for Nottinghamshire and England can be found in Table 2a of the following file:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635104/SFR39-2017-MainTables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635104/SFR39-2017-MainTables.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We do not publish information for progression to Russell Group universities on this basis. However, figures for the percentage of 15 year old pupils from state-funded and special schools by free school meal status who entered the most selective HE institutions by age 19 by local authority and region were published as part of the Social Mobility Index. The most selective institutions are defined as the top third of providers, ranked by the average Universities and Colleges Admissions Service tariff score.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for Nottinghamshire and England for the latest three years are available in the Selective HE sheet of the following file: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662507/SMI_2017_Final_v1.1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662507/SMI_2017_Final_v1.1.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not available at parliamentary constituency level.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","127802","2018-02-20T14:25:04.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839245/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839245/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Higher Education: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what percentage of young people eligible for free school meals at 15 in (a) Ashfield constituency, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) England entered higher education by the age of 19 in each of the last three years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","127799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839246","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Department does not collate this information centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","127834","2018-02-22T17:12:00.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839246/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839246/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-08","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2018 to Question 125090 on Travellers: Caravan Sites, how many local planning authorities development plan documents were found to be consistent with planning policy for Traveller Sites.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","127800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839247","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-26","<p>The procedure for interventions in mergers by Ministers on public interest grounds, including national security, is set out in the Enterprise Act 2002.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-26T15:34:16.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839247/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839247/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","GKN: Melrose","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the timetable is for his Department to make a decision any investigation into the proposed takeover of GKN Plc by Melrose Industries in the interests of National Security.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","127801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839248","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The department publishes information on the percentage of 15 year old pupils from state-funded and special schools by free school meal status who entered higher education (HE) by age 19 by local authority and region.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for Nottinghamshire and England can be found in Table 2a of the following file:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635104/SFR39-2017-MainTables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/635104/SFR39-2017-MainTables.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We do not publish information for progression to Russell Group universities on this basis. However, figures for the percentage of 15 year old pupils from state-funded and special schools by free school meal status who entered the most selective HE institutions by age 19 by local authority and region were published as part of the Social Mobility Index. The most selective institutions are defined as the top third of providers, ranked by the average Universities and Colleges Admissions Service tariff score.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for Nottinghamshire and England for the latest three years are available in the Selective HE sheet of the following file: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662507/SMI_2017_Final_v1.1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/662507/SMI_2017_Final_v1.1.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Data is not available at parliamentary constituency level.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","127799","2018-02-20T14:25:04.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839248/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839248/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Universities: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many and what percentage of young people eligible for free school meals at 15 from (a) Ashfield constituency, (b) Nottinghamshire and (c) England entered higher education at a Russell Group university in each of the last three years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","127802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839249","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-20","<p>Parents call the childcare service helpline for a variety of reasons relating to the Tax-Free Childcare or 30 hours free childcare schemes. HMRC does not hold data about the number of parents who call before or while making an application for Tax-Free Childcare subsequently submit an application.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Education is responsible for 30 hours free childcare guidance. The childcare service helpline provides advice to parents who have a change in circumstances.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","127804","2018-02-20T12:52:18.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839249/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839249/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-08","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2018 to Question 124116 on Children: Daycare, how many of the callers to the childcare service helpline successfully completed their application for Tax-Free Childcare.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","127803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839250","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-20","<p>Parents call the childcare service helpline for a variety of reasons relating to the Tax-Free Childcare or 30 hours free childcare schemes. HMRC does not hold data about the number of parents who call before or while making an application for Tax-Free Childcare subsequently submit an application.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Education is responsible for 30 hours free childcare guidance. The childcare service helpline provides advice to parents who have a change in circumstances.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","127803","2018-02-20T12:52:18.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839250/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839250/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-08","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what guidance his Department has issued on  30 hours free childcare provision to parents whose job circumstances change in the rolling three-month period.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","127804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839251","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>Public Health England supports local areas in responding to the threat from fentanyl, and other drugs. This includes ensuring wider availability of the opioid-overdose antidote naloxone, providing messages to use with people at risk, and issuing public health alerts when there is sufficient evidence of harm from particular drugs like fentanyl.</p><p>Local authorities are responsible for commissioning drug treatment services and interventions to reduce drug-related harm, based on local need.</p><p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Home Secretary has also asked the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs to investigate the risks around fentanyl analogues, so we can maximise the effectiveness of our response.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-20T17:15:15.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839251/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839251/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Fentanyl: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent steps the Government has taken to tackle the misuse of Fentanyl.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","127805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839252","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-20T17:14:00.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839252/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839252/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the top ten drugs bought by the NHS from EU countries were by (a) volume and (b) price.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","127806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839253","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-20","<p>UK-funded partners have been delivering humanitarian assistance in Afrin including health and protection services. Activities inside Afrin are currently suspended due to the recent military action. Partners are pre-positioning supplies to help meet the needs of those fleeing the area. We call on all parties to facilitate access for life-saving humanitarian aid, and to allow freedom of movement for those caught up in the violence, in accordance with international humanitarian law.</p><p> </p><p>The UK will continue to engage with the Government of Turkey on issues relating to the current operation. The Prime Minister spoke to President Erdogan on 26 January where she urged Turkey to avoid any escalation in violence and to protect civilians, while recognising its legitimate interest in the security of its borders.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-20T13:46:44.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839253/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839253/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-08","Syria: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government taking to help alleviate the humanitarian situation in Afrin.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","127807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839254","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>UK ports operate on a commercial basis generally without public sector financial support. As such, ports are responsible for identifying and funding their own investment requirements. UK ports have an impressive record of investment in new and existing facilities since 2010, including substantial investments at London Gateway, Liverpool, Felixstowe, Southampton and Dover amongst others. Financial support from the UK government and European Union was secured for a small number of investments.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127809","2018-02-26T15:07:14.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839254/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839254/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Ports: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the amount of (a) public and (b) private funding was invested in (i) new and (ii) existing ports infrastructure was in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839255","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>UK ports operate on a commercial basis generally without public sector financial support. As such, ports are responsible for identifying and funding their own investment requirements. UK ports have an impressive record of investment in new and existing facilities since 2010, including substantial investments at London Gateway, Liverpool, Felixstowe, Southampton and Dover amongst others. Financial support from the UK government and European Union was secured for a small number of investments.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127808","2018-02-26T15:07:14.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839255/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839255/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Ports: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the the adequacy of levels of (a) public and (b) private investment in UK ports infrastructure in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127809"
