"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839257","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government has been undertaking rigorous and extensive analysis work to support our exit negotiations, as a responsible Government should, in order to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks. We have been engaging with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, including ports and maritime; and with all regions of the UK as part of this process, and we will continue to do so as we move forward.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127812","2018-02-26T16:44:44.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839257/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839257/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Shipping: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on rates of (a) employment and (b) training for UK-based seafarers.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839258","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government has been undertaking rigorous and extensive analysis work to support our exit negotiations, as a responsible Government should, in order to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks. We have been engaging with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, including ports and maritime; and with all regions of the UK as part of this process, and we will continue to do so as we move forward.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127811","2018-02-26T16:44:44.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839258/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839258/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Ports: Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on annual rates of freight tonnage traffic handled at UK ports.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839259","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government has been undertaking rigorous and extensive analysis work to support our exit negotiations, as a responsible Government should, in order to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks. We have been engaging with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, including ports and maritime; and with all regions of the UK as part of this process, and we will continue to do so as we move forward.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, on leaving the EU, the UK will also be leaving the Single Market and the Customs Union. The Future Partnership paper ‘Future Customs Arrangements’, published last year, put forward two proposed approaches for the UK’s future customs relationship with the EU. One is a highly streamlined customs arrangement, and the other is a new customs partnership. The precise form of any new agreement will be the subject of negotiation.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127814 ; 127815","2018-02-26T16:47:53.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839259/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839259/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect on the shipping industry of the UK (a) remaining and (b) becoming part of (i) the single market and (ii) a customs union with the European Union.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839260","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government has been undertaking rigorous and extensive analysis work to support our exit negotiations, as a responsible Government should, in order to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks. We have been engaging with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, including ports and maritime; and with all regions of the UK as part of this process, and we will continue to do so as we move forward.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, on leaving the EU, the UK will also be leaving the Single Market and the Customs Union. The Future Partnership paper ‘Future Customs Arrangements’, published last year, put forward two proposed approaches for the UK’s future customs relationship with the EU. One is a highly streamlined customs arrangement, and the other is a new customs partnership. The precise form of any new agreement will be the subject of negotiation.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127813 ; 127815","2018-02-26T16:47:53.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839260/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839260/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839260/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect on the ports sector in the UK of (a) remaining or (b) becoming part of (i) the single market or (ii) a customs union with the EU.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839261","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government has been undertaking rigorous and extensive analysis work to support our exit negotiations, as a responsible Government should, in order to inform our understanding of how EU exit will affect the UK’s domestic policies and frameworks. We have been engaging with businesses and industry bodies from all sectors of the economy, including ports and maritime; and with all regions of the UK as part of this process, and we will continue to do so as we move forward.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has made clear, on leaving the EU, the UK will also be leaving the Single Market and the Customs Union. The Future Partnership paper ‘Future Customs Arrangements’, published last year, put forward two proposed approaches for the UK’s future customs relationship with the EU. One is a highly streamlined customs arrangement, and the other is a new customs partnership. The precise form of any new agreement will be the subject of negotiation.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani","127813 ; 127814","2018-02-26T16:47:53.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839261/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839261/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Shipping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect on the maritime services sector of the UK (a) remaining or (b) becoming part of (i) the single market or (ii) a customs union with the EU.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","127815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839262","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>We have made assessments on other countries regarding their energy policy. In those countries where there were, or had been, price interventions in the energy sector markets were either not previously liberalised, or had only recently been liberalised. This is very different to the situation in Great Britain, and so no useful comparisons can be drawn on the effect on employment and investment in those countries.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-20T17:25:41.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839262/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839262/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the answer of 30 January 2018 to Question 124845, on Energy: Prices, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of energy price caps on (a) consumers (b) employment and (c) investment in (i) Canada, (ii) the US, (iii) Spain and (iv) New Zealand; and if his Department will publish that assessment.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","127816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839263","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Government expects to publish its response shortly.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-22T17:13:15.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839263/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839263/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-08","Building Regulations: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when the Government plans to respond to the ninth report of the Women and Equalities Committee's report, Building for Equality: Disability and the Built Environment of Session 2016-17, HC 631, published on 25 April 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","127817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839264","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>The draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill is clear that Ofgem must have regard to the need to ensure that holders of supply licences who operate efficiently are able to finance activities authorised by the licence. It would be for the independent regulator, Ofgem, to make its assessment of efficient operations.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-20T14:55:28.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839264/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839264/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill on employment in energy projects in the counties and regions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","127818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839265","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>In designing the method for setting the level of the price cap we would expect that Ofgem would need to consider how to take account of relevant changes in wholesale energy prices, whilst maintaining incentives for switching and enabling effective competition.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-02-20T14:54:42.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839265/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839265/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of implementation of proposals in the draft Domestic Gas and Electricity (Tariff Cap) Bill on a (a) a rise and (b) fall in wholesale energy costs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","127819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839266","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-23","<p>NHS England remains committed to the implementation of Faecal Immunochemical Test (FIT) within the NHS Bowel Cancer Screening Programme from 2018.</p><p> </p><p>During 2018, NHS England will finalise a number of practical steps to ensure that when Faecal Immunochemical Test is implemented, it is sustainable. This includes working with Public Health England, who will be ensuring that the practical arrangements for managing the production and distribution of FIT kits are in place, and working with local providers to ensure sufficient workforce capacity is in place to deliver FIT and save lives. These practical steps will enable NHS England to confirm the specific date in 2018 when FIT will replace Faecal Occult Blood testing.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-23T12:55:43.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839266/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839266/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Bowel Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the timescale is for the introduction of the Faecal Immunochemical Test to the bowel screening programme.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","127820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839267","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The department expects schools to use their full budget to provide the best possible education for all their pupils, including those with Special Educational Needs (SEN). The department believes that headteachers are best placed to make decisions about how to spend their budgets, and have no plans to ring-fence SEN funding. Schools are held to account for the progress their pupils make through the school accountability system and Ofsted inspection.</p><p> </p><p>There is a robust SEN system in place, that has been strengthened still further in recent years. The department has high expectations of schools over the support they should provide to pupils with SEN, and these can be seen for example in the statutory duties on schools to:</p><ul><li>use their best endeavours to make provision for a pupil’s SEN.</li><li>have a SEN Co-ordinator with a Masters level specialist qualification.</li><li>publish a SEN Information Report setting out how they implement their SEN policy.</li><li>comply with the Equality Act 2010.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The government takes account of the implications for pupils with SEN and disabilities whenever new policies are developed. For example, the introduction of Progress 8 and new primary progress measures have strengthened the expectations on schools to support the progress of all their pupils, thereby adding greater weight to the effectiveness of the support schools provide to their pupils with SEN.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","127822","2018-02-21T16:31:33.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839267/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839267/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Special Educational Needs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how mainstream schools are held to account for the use of SEND funding; and whether the Government plans to ring-fence that funding.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","127821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839268","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The department expects schools to use their full budget to provide the best possible education for all their pupils, including those with Special Educational Needs (SEN). The department believes that headteachers are best placed to make decisions about how to spend their budgets, and have no plans to ring-fence SEN funding. Schools are held to account for the progress their pupils make through the school accountability system and Ofsted inspection.</p><p> </p><p>There is a robust SEN system in place, that has been strengthened still further in recent years. The department has high expectations of schools over the support they should provide to pupils with SEN, and these can be seen for example in the statutory duties on schools to:</p><ul><li>use their best endeavours to make provision for a pupil’s SEN.</li><li>have a SEN Co-ordinator with a Masters level specialist qualification.</li><li>publish a SEN Information Report setting out how they implement their SEN policy.</li><li>comply with the Equality Act 2010.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The government takes account of the implications for pupils with SEN and disabilities whenever new policies are developed. For example, the introduction of Progress 8 and new primary progress measures have strengthened the expectations on schools to support the progress of all their pupils, thereby adding greater weight to the effectiveness of the support schools provide to their pupils with SEN.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","127821","2018-02-21T16:31:33.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839268/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839268/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department takes to ensure that learners on SEND support in mainstream settings are prioritised by school leadership.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","127822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839269","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The Department is currently consulting on all aspects of the proposals to strengthen Qualified Teacher Status. As part of this, we have proposed introducing an early career content framework for newly qualified teachers, and have suggested that special educational needs and disabilities could be a key element of this framework. The consultation is currently open and we will aim to publish a response by summer 2018.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-21T13:10:20.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839269/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839269/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Special Educational Needs: Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps he is taking to ensure that SEND is a fundamental part of strengthening Qualified Teacher Status.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","127823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839270","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>Special educational needs Co-ordinators (SENCO)s play an essential role in schools, supporting teaching staff to meet the needs of pupils with Special educational needs (SEN) and ensuring that schools have a clear and effective approach to inclusive education. All maintained mainstream nurseries, schools and academies (including free schools) are required to have a named SENCO who is a qualified teacher. To support their development, SENCOs must undertake the National Award in SEN Coordination award within three years of taking up role. The SENCO has an important role to play with the headteacher and governing body, in determining the strategic development of SEN policy and provision in the school. They will be most effective in that role if they are part of the school leadership team.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As part of the consultation to strengthen Qualified Teacher Status, we have proposed introducing an early career content framework for all newly qualified teachers, and have suggested that SEND could be a key element of this framework. The consultation is currently open and we will use the responses to help understand how to best support those interested in becoming SEND specialists. We aim to publish a response by summer 2018.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-21T13:21:47.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839270/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839270/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839270/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to improve career progression opportunities for special educational needs coordinators and SEND specialists; and whether he plans to include those roles in his Department's consultation, Strengthening qualified teacher status and career progression, published on 15 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","127824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839271","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-20","<p>The department will consider the usage of the Severn Tunnel Junction when specifying the requirements for the next Great Western Direct Award and Cross Country franchise. A public consultation for the Great Western franchise is already under way, inviting views on future priorities and this closes on 21 February 2018. We will be consulting on the future Cross Country franchise in due course.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-02-20T14:18:48.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839271/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839271/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","Railways: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the usage of the Severn Tunnel Junction will be considered when the (a) Cross Country and (b) Great Western franchise agreements are drawn up.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","127825"
