"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839273","Prime Minister","false","2018-02-20","<p>I have regular meetings with ministerial colleagues, officials and others.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2018-02-20T17:54:23.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839273/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839273/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2018-02-08","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many times she met with (a) Alan Milburn in his capacity as Chair or (b) Baroness Gillian Shephard in her capacity as Deputy Chair of the Social Mobility Commission during their tenure at that Commission.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","127827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839274","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","127832","2018-03-01T16:43:50.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839274/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839274/answer","PQ127828_ 127832.pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839274/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-08","Employment: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the number of insecure jobs in (a) the North West and (b) Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839275","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not made an estimate of the number of self-employed people earning below the National Living Wage. The legal entitlement to receive the National Minimum Wage or National Living Wage does not apply to the self-employed.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-20T12:11:38.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839275/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839275/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Self-employed: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the number of self-employed people who earn below the national living wage in (a) the North West and (b) Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839276","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-21","<p>As set out in the Industrial Strategy White Paper, this Government is determined that everyone should benefit from the changes that new technologies will continue to bring. What we have seen throughout history is that technological change has delivered more jobs, and we now have record employment. There may be challenging transitions to make for some as work changes, but the future lies in support that promotes work and is increasingly tailored to the needs of the individual, not a single payment for everyone.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made an assessment of the impact of the increase in automation. However we believe that Universal Credit is the right approach for a changing economy, because it simplifies the benefit system, targets resources according to need, and pays people flexibly as their working circumstances change, and ensures that work always pays.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-21T14:57:13.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839276/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839276/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-08","Automation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the increase in the number automated jobs on the potential merits of introducing a universal basic income.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839277","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>Through our Industrial Strategy, we are exploring how to utilise technological change to improve participation and progression in the labour market, for people from under-represented groups. This includes those with BAME backgrounds, people with disabilities and people from lower socio-economic backgrounds.</p><p> </p><p>Embedding AI across the UK will create thousands of good quality jobs and drive economic growth. A recent study found digital technologies including AI created a net total of 80,000 new jobs annually across a population similar to the UK[1].</p><p> </p><p>Building on the recommendations of the Royal Society and British Academy review, we are creating the Centre for Data Ethics and Innovation, dedicated to informing decisions on stewardship for the uses and impacts of new data technologies.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Mckinsey (2017), ‘Shaping the future of work in Europe’s 9 digital front-runner countries’ <a href="https://www.mckinsey.com/global-themes/europe/shaping-the-future-of-work-in-eu-ropes-nine-digital-front-runner-countries" target="_blank">https://www.mckinsey.com/global-themes/europe/shaping-the-future-of-work-in-eu-ropes-nine-digital-front-runner-countries</a></p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-20T12:12:31.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839277/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839277/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839277/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Automation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of the automation of jobs on (a) women, (b) BAME people, (c) disabled people and (d) people from lower socio-economic backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839278","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith","127828","2018-03-01T16:43:50.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839278/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839278/answer","PQ127828_ 127832.pdf","UKSA Response ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839278/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-08","Zero Hours Contracts: Liverpool Walton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in Liverpool Walton constituency are employed on zero-hour contracts.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839279","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The Government’s priority has been to ensure schools can continue to operate as usual. The Government is supporting the Official Receiver, so that services to schools and other public services can continue to be delivered.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities and academy trusts are responsible for their own contracts. The Government has, however, planned extensively and has been working with local authorities and academy trusts to make sure contingency plans are being implemented, if required. Information available to the Department indicates that the number of local authority and academy trust schools covered under catering, facilities management or other service contracts with Carillion is relatively low.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is continuing to monitor the situation and will work with schools to help minimise any disruption for pupils.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-21T13:24:54.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839279/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839279/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839279/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the liquidation of Carillion on schools in Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839280","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Department does not collate this information centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","127800","2018-02-22T17:12:01.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839280/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839280/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839280/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-08","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2018 to Question 125090, how many local planning authorities have had their development plan documents assessed and found to be inconsistent with planning policy for Traveller sites.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","127834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839281","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The Government is ensuring young people have the knowledge to challenge attitudes about abuse and consent. The Home Office’s campaign “Disrespect NoBody” aims to prevent the onset of domestic violence in adults by challenging attitudes and behaviours amongst teenage boys and girls.</p><p>The Department is considering how best to ensure pupils are taught about healthy and respectful relationships as part of Relationships Education in primary and Relationships and Sex Education in secondary schools. The Department has been engaging with a broad range of expert organisations, and via a public call for evidence, about the potential content for these compulsory subjects and in considering whether to make Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education compulsory. The Department will formally consult on draft regulations and guidance before laying regulations in the House for debate.</p><p>Schools and colleges must have regard to statutory guidance Keeping Children Safe in Education (KCSIE) when carrying out their duties to safeguard and promote the welfare of children. KCSIE states that schools should ensure children are taught about safeguarding, including online safety.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-21T16:27:58.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839281/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839281/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839281/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Personal, Social, Health and Economic Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that all schools teach awareness of violence against women and girls.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839282","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The full time equivalent number and percentage of unqualified teachers in state funded primary and secondary schools in the Liverpool Walton constituency is shown in the table attached.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-21T13:28:27.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839282/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839282/answer","127836 attachment.docx","FTE no of unqualified teachers in Liverpool Walton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839282/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Teachers: Liverpool Walton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate he has made of the number of unqualified teachers in (a) primary and (b) secondary schools in Liverpool Walton constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839283","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>Advice to Inspectors on examining assessments of gypsy and traveller accommodation needs within development plan documents is provided in the Inspector Training Manual and in Inspector training sessions.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-22T17:04:13.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839283/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839283/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839283/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-08","Travellers: Caravan Sites","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 2 February 2018 to Question 125090, what training planning inspectors tasked with examining development plan documents receive with regard to the assessment of the accommodation needs of Gypsies and Travellers.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","127837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839284","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>The public sector pay cap is no longer in place and we have adopted a more flexible approach to public sector pay. The Department set out in their latest remit to the School Teachers’ Review Body (STRB) that they should utilise this flexibility to target the next pay award to promote recruitment and retention.</p><p> </p><p>The fundamental changes to teachers’ pay that have been introduced over the last four years following the STRB’s recommendations have given greater autonomy to schools to decide how to reward their staff. This increased flexibility helps schools to attract and retain the best teachers and to target any school-level recruitment and retention problems they may have, including in specific subjects.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2018-02-21T13:41:23.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839284/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839284/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839284/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Schools: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the public sector pay cap on the recruitment and retention of staff in schools in (a) the UK, (b) the North West and (c) Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839285","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>Due to the wide range of services that affect educational outcomes for young children, it is not possible to draw a causal link between children’s centre services and a child’s educational attainment. Early Years Foundation Stage Profile (EYFSP) results show that the proportion of young children achieving a good level of development at age five has increased across Liverpool 2010. EYFSP results from 2009-10 to 2016-17 are published at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-early-years-foundation-stage-profile" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/statistics-early-years-foundation-stage-profile</a>.</p><p> </p><p>If a council decides to close a children’s centre, statutory guidance is clear that they should demonstrate that local children and families would not be adversely affected and local areas continue to have sufficient children’s centres to meet their needs.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-21T13:31:31.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839285/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839285/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839285/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Children's Centres: Liverpool Walton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the closure of Sure Start children’s centres on the school readiness of children in Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839286","Department for Education","false","2018-02-21","<p>Widening participation is a central priority for this government. The department will continue to ensure that everyone has the opportunity to benefit from a university education, regardless of background or where they grew up.</p><p> </p><p>University application rates for 18-year-olds to full-time study remain at record levels, including those from disadvantaged areas.</p><p> </p><p>The independent Office for Fair Access, led by the Director of Fair Access (DfA), is the regulator currently responsible for widening access to higher education (HE) in England (a function that will soon transfer to the Office for Students). HE providers wishing to charge tuition fees above the basic fee level must have an Access Agreement, setting out their targets and planned expenditure to improve access for disadvantaged and under-represented groups, and approved by the DfA.</p><p> </p><p>The department is introducing sweeping reforms through legislation. The Office for Students (OfS) will have a statutory duty to promote equality of opportunity, across the whole lifecycle for disadvantaged students, not just access. As a result, widening access and participation will be at the core of the OfS’ functions. The department’s reforms will introduce a Transparency Duty requiring HE providers to publish application, offer, acceptance, dropout and attainment rates of students by ethnicity, gender and socio-economic background. This will help to hold the sector to account for their record on access and retention of students from lower socio-economic backgrounds.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-02-21T13:33:32.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839286/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839286/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839286/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Universities: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of people from lower socio-economic backgrounds applying to university.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839287","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The following table shows the total spend for web advertising and the disaggregated spend for each type of advert over the last three years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2017-18 (as of 30 Sep 2017)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Job Boards</p></td><td><p>£790,000</p></td><td><p>£650,000</p></td><td><p>£420,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Display</p></td><td><p>£970,000</p></td><td><p>£1,360,000</p></td><td><p>£940,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Search</p></td><td><p>£470,000</p></td><td><p>£360,000</p></td><td><p>£200,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid Social</p></td><td><p>£190,000</p></td><td><p>£780,000</p></td><td><p>£450,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£2,420,000</p></td><td><p>£3,170,000</p></td><td><p>£2,000,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Definitions for each type of advert:</p><p>Job Boards - Job advertising sites, which are used to promote Army jobs.</p><p>Display – Banner adverts that appear on websites.</p><p>Search – The cost to return an advert on Google search listings, which will appear higher up search listings.</p><p>Paid Social – Content paid to be placed on Social Media sites Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.</p><p>Advertisements are placed through the Cabinet Office Media Buying Agency. They use algorithms to target audiences, rather than advertising on specific websites, meaning adverts may appear on a number of online platforms that carry advertising. As of 21 September 2017, there were 1,173 approved websites listed on the latest Cabinet Office Government Whitelist.</p><p>For presentational purposes, figures have been rounded to the nearest £10,000 to improve the clarity of output and convey an appropriate level of precision.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","127842","2018-02-20T17:07:55.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839287/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839287/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839287/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, on which websites Army recruitment advertisements have been placed in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839288","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The following table shows the total spend for web advertising and the disaggregated spend for each type of advert over the last three years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2016-17</p></td><td><p>Recruiting Year 2017-18 (as of 30 Sep 2017)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Job Boards</p></td><td><p>£790,000</p></td><td><p>£650,000</p></td><td><p>£420,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Display</p></td><td><p>£970,000</p></td><td><p>£1,360,000</p></td><td><p>£940,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Search</p></td><td><p>£470,000</p></td><td><p>£360,000</p></td><td><p>£200,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Paid Social</p></td><td><p>£190,000</p></td><td><p>£780,000</p></td><td><p>£450,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£2,420,000</p></td><td><p>£3,170,000</p></td><td><p>£2,000,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Definitions for each type of advert:</p><p>Job Boards - Job advertising sites, which are used to promote Army jobs.</p><p>Display – Banner adverts that appear on websites.</p><p>Search – The cost to return an advert on Google search listings, which will appear higher up search listings.</p><p>Paid Social – Content paid to be placed on Social Media sites Facebook, Twitter and Instagram.</p><p>Advertisements are placed through the Cabinet Office Media Buying Agency. They use algorithms to target audiences, rather than advertising on specific websites, meaning adverts may appear on a number of online platforms that carry advertising. As of 21 September 2017, there were 1,173 approved websites listed on the latest Cabinet Office Government Whitelist.</p><p>For presentational purposes, figures have been rounded to the nearest £10,000 to improve the clarity of output and convey an appropriate level of precision.</p><p> </p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","127841","2018-02-20T17:07:55.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839288/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839288/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839288/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the (a) total and (b) disaggregated spend was on each website where army recruitment advertisements have been placed in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839289","Cabinet Office","false","2018-03-20","<p>The Minister for the Cabinet Office has not met with the Social Mobility Commission since his appointment.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-03-20T11:22:50.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839289/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839289/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839289/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839289/answer/previousversion/41925","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-02-08","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many meetings he has had with the Social Mobility Commission since his appointment.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","127843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839290","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The total spend for Army recruitment advertising over the past three years on Facebook and Twitter is shown in the table below. There was no spend on Snapchat.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18 (Up to 31 December 2017)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Facebook</p></td><td><p>£844,000</p></td><td><p>£1,076,000</p></td><td><p>£481,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Twitter</p></td><td><p>£161,000</p></td><td><p>£218,000</p></td><td><p>£41,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures above include £2,000 spent boosting Facebook posts in 2016-17 and £19,400 in 2017-18.</p><p>The target audience for boosted Facebook posts are those aged between 16 and 24 for the Regular Army and between 16 and 35 for the Reserves that have expressed an interest in a career with the British Army.</p><p> </p><p>For presentational purposes, figures have been rounded to the nearest £1,000 to improve the clarity of output and convey an appropriate level of precision. Figures are a single Service estimate.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127845","2018-02-20T17:35:29.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839290/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839290/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839290/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the total spend was on army recruitment advertising via (a) Facebook, (b) Snapchat and (c) Twitter in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839291","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The total spend for Army recruitment advertising over the past three years on Facebook and Twitter is shown in the table below. There was no spend on Snapchat.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2015-16</p></td><td><p>Financial Year 2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18 (Up to 31 December 2017)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Facebook</p></td><td><p>£844,000</p></td><td><p>£1,076,000</p></td><td><p>£481,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Twitter</p></td><td><p>£161,000</p></td><td><p>£218,000</p></td><td><p>£41,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures above include £2,000 spent boosting Facebook posts in 2016-17 and £19,400 in 2017-18.</p><p>The target audience for boosted Facebook posts are those aged between 16 and 24 for the Regular Army and between 16 and 35 for the Reserves that have expressed an interest in a career with the British Army.</p><p> </p><p>For presentational purposes, figures have been rounded to the nearest £1,000 to improve the clarity of output and convey an appropriate level of precision. Figures are a single Service estimate.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","127844","2018-02-20T17:35:30.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839291/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839291/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839291/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Army: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department has spent to boost posts on the Army Jobs Facebook page in each of the last three years; and what the target audience was for each of those posts.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","127845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839292","Home Office","false","2018-02-21","<p>The Office for National Statistics publishes information on the number of incidents of domestic abuse recorded by the police.</p><p>This information is published by police force area in a cross government statistical bulletin ‘Domestic abuse in England and Wales: year ending March 2017’, which can be found at the link below. Data are not available at the constituency or borough level.</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/bulletins/domesticabuseinenglandandwales/yearendingmarch2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice/bulletins/domesticabuseinenglandandwales/yearendingmarch2017</a></p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-02-21T11:18:15.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839292/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839292/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839292/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-08","Domestic Abuse: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many recorded incidents of domestic violence there were in (a) Leigh constituency and (b) Wigan Borough in each of the last ten years.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","127846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839293","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Ministry of Defence keeps the remunerative and non-remunerative offer for members of the Armed Forces under review to ensure it is fit for purpose in attracting and retaining the skills we need to support Defence. There are currently no plans to introduce a new pension scheme for existing members of the Armed Forces.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-02-20T16:37:08.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839293/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839293/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839293/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Armed Forces: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to introduce a new pension scheme for members of the armed forces; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","127847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839294","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Government recognises the unique commitment that Service families make to their country and remains sympathetic to the circumstances of this group of widows. However, there are no plans to review the rules relating to widows, on the Armed Forces Pension Scheme that remarried prior to 1 April 2015.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-02-20T16:38:46.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839294/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839294/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-02-08","Armed Forces: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will review the rules of the Armed Forces Pension Scheme relating to widows who remarried prior to 1 April 2015.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","127848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839295","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Secretary of State has set out plans to consult shortly on a new, independent and statutory body to hold Government, and potentially public authorities, to account on environmental commitments once we have left the EU. We are also proposing to consult on the creation of a new policy statement on environmental principles to apply when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-02-22T15:29:36.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839295/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839295/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-02-08","Environment Protection: Enforcement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what consultation is planned to engage businesses and other stakeholders on the development of proposals for a new environmental enforcement agency to ensure good governance after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","127849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839296","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>Companies House ensures it has the appropriate amount of resources to effectively manage the register, including undertaking the required level of enforcement of the register of People of Significant Control. Staffing levels for 2018/19 have yet to be finalised but these will be made available in its Business Plan which will be published before the next financial year.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-20T15:35:38.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839296/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839296/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Companies House: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 22 January 2018 to Question 123021, what information his Department holds on the number of staff who will be recruited to Companies House in 2018-19; and what plans he has to increase recruitment to that organisation after the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","127850"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839297","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-02-20","<p>There are no current plans to introduce automated verification of beneficial ownership information.</p><p> </p><p>However, Companies House is undertaking a number of activities to improve the quality of information relating to beneficial ownership, the People with Significant Control (PSC) data, on the register, including:</p><p> </p><p>1. contacting companies where they believe the company has misunderstood the requirements, to ensure that the records are corrected and that they comply with their legal requirements;</p><p>2. pursuing companies that have not provided PSC information in their confirmation statement or that have not provided a statement of additional matters;</p><p>3. following up with companies and PSCs where they have issued notices to their PSC (asking the PSCs to provide them with information), or restrictions (where a PSC has failed to provide information), to ensure they update the information on their company records;</p><p>4. seeking compliance from companies where there has been a complaint about missing or incorrect PSC information.</p><p> </p><p>The cost of maintaining the entire public register in 2016/17 was £56.6m. Staff costs were £28.5m and non-staff administration costs were £28.1m. Further information can be found in the Companies House Annual Report and Accounts for 2016/17.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-02-20T15:34:41.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839297/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839297/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-02-08","Companies: Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to introduce automated verification systems in Companies House to check the accuracy of the register of beneficial ownership for companies; and how much it costs to maintain the public register each year with regards to staff, IT and any associated overheads.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","127851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839298","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government is fully aware of the importance of molybdenum-99 (Mo-99) supplies for the National Health Service. However, Euratom places no restrictions on the export of medical isotopes to countries outside the European Union. Therefore, the United Kingdom’s ability to import medical isotopes from Europe and the rest of the world, will not be affected by withdrawal from Euratom.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the concern that changes to customs and border processes as a result of withdrawal from the EU and the EU Customs Union could affect the timely supply of medical radioisotopes. It is in the interest of both the UK and EU to avoid disruption in the timely access of treatment to patients; and to ensure that cross-border trade with the EU is frictionless as possible. Continued access to these critical products remains a high priority topic for the Government in both our domestic preparations as well as in our negotiations on our future relationship with the EU.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","127855","2018-02-26T17:12:16.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839298/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839298/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Molybdenum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how the Government plans to supply molybdenum-9, used for the manufacture of technetium-99 generators after the UK leaves Euratom.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","127852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839299","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>​Officials from our Embassy to Tel Aviv most recently discussed the issue of demolitions of Palestinian property with the Israeli authorities on 19 February. On 6 February, the EU released a local statement expressing strong concerns about demolition by the Israeli authorities of parts of the school of the Bedouin community of Abu Nuwar. Demolitions and evictions of Palestinians from their homes cause unnecessary suffering to ordinary Palestinians; call into question Israel’s commitment to a viable two-state solution; and, in all but the most exceptional cases, are contrary to International Humanitarian Law.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-02-20T16:54:42.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839299/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839299/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-02-08","West Bank: Demolition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Israeli Government on the demolition of EU-funded structures in the village of Abu Nuwar in the West Bank; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","127853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839300","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>Molybdenum-99 (Mo-99) is currently made in nuclear research reactors. There are currently six active reactors in the world that produce more than 90% of the world’s Mo-99 supply, the following table lists these reactors and their location. Australia and South Africa are not members of Euratom.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Reactor</p></td><td><p>Location</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HFR</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Netherlands</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>BR-2</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td><td><p>Belgium</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Safari-1</p></td><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>South Africa</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MARIA</p></td><td><p>Poland</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>OPAL</p></td><td><p>Australia</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>LVR-15</p></td><td><p>Czech Republic</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-02-20T17:09:29.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839300/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839300/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Molybdenum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will publish a list of current suppliers of molybdenum-99 located in countries that are not members of Euratom.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","127854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839301","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-26","<p>The Government is fully aware of the importance of molybdenum-99 (Mo-99) supplies for the National Health Service. However, Euratom places no restrictions on the export of medical isotopes to countries outside the European Union. Therefore, the United Kingdom’s ability to import medical isotopes from Europe and the rest of the world, will not be affected by withdrawal from Euratom.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the concern that changes to customs and border processes as a result of withdrawal from the EU and the EU Customs Union could affect the timely supply of medical radioisotopes. It is in the interest of both the UK and EU to avoid disruption in the timely access of treatment to patients; and to ensure that cross-border trade with the EU is frictionless as possible. Continued access to these critical products remains a high priority topic for the Government in both our domestic preparations as well as in our negotiations on our future relationship with the EU.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine","127852","2018-02-26T17:12:16.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839301/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839301/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-08","Molybdenum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to ensure the continued supply of molybdenum-99 after UK leaves Euratom.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","127855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839302","HM Treasury","false","2018-02-20","<p>Since 2010, over 9700 people in England and Wales have been successfully convicted for money laundering offences – most of these are under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA) which provides for various money laundering offences, including where an individual knows or suspects they may be facilitating money laundering or seeks to conceal criminal property. The Money Laundering Regulations 2007 and the subsequent update, the Money Laundering Regulations 2017 (MLRs) focus on ensuring regulated businesses put in place controls to guard against money laundering or terrorist finance. Supervisors are appointed by the Treasury to monitor compliance with these regulations and primarily use a range of supervisory tools to promote compliance, including warning notices, action plans, financial penalties or withdrawal of the right to practice. The vast majority of breaches of the MLRs are remedied or penalised using these supervisory tools. Since 2010 there were over 3,539 fines issued on firms and individuals across the regime.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-02-20T17:16:01.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839302/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839302/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-02-08","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people have been (a) convicted and (b) fined under the Money Laundering Regulations 2007 by offence since 2010.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","127856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839303","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-20","<p>The estimated total cost for Thameslink Programme London Bridge Station infrastructure works including civils works and associated Railway Systems is £1.6 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Of this total cost, the cost of the railway systems work, including track and signalling at London Bridge station and on its approaches, was £508 million at January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The overall package has delivered major capacity enhancements, and, with 24 Thameslink trains per hour being able to run at peak times through the central London core from 2019, the station concourse now has two-thirds more space for passengers and it will have the ability to cope with 96 million passengers per year, up from the 54 million today.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","127858","2018-02-20T16:41:40.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839303/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839303/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","London Bridge Station: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the total cost of the Thameslink project at London Bridge; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","127857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839304","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-20","<p>The estimated total cost for Thameslink Programme London Bridge Station infrastructure works including civils works and associated Railway Systems is £1.6 billion.</p><p> </p><p>Of this total cost, the cost of the railway systems work, including track and signalling at London Bridge station and on its approaches, was £508 million at January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The overall package has delivered major capacity enhancements, and, with 24 Thameslink trains per hour being able to run at peak times through the central London core from 2019, the station concourse now has two-thirds more space for passengers and it will have the ability to cope with 96 million passengers per year, up from the 54 million today.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","127857","2018-02-20T16:41:40.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839304/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839304/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","London Bridge Station: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much money from the public purse has been spent on the Thameslink project to improve the infrastructure to all rail lines that run (a) into and (b) out of London Bridge Station; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","127858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839305","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-20","<p>Through CDC, the UK’s Development Finance Institution, DFID has invested a total of $8.8m in Bridge International Academies (BIA) for its global operations in Africa and India. An investment of $1.6m was made in 2016. The remainder was invested in 2013 and 2014. These are long term capital investments made to fund expansion of BIA’s business in Africa. In addition, a DFID £3.45m grant, awarded competitively, was also provided to open 23 Bridge academies in Lagos, Nigeria. This grant is now completed. There are no current plans to provide additional funding.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2018-02-20T13:47:13.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839305/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839305/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-08","Bridge International Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what plans her Department has to provide funding (a) directly and (b) indirectly to (i) Bridge International Academies and (ii) its parent or subsidiary companies.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","127859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839306","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>Since 2014, state funded schools in England have been required by law to provide free lunches to all children in reception, Year 1 and Year 2, under the universal infant fee school meals policy. The criteria are not age related. The legislation is clear that local authorities must provide a free meal to a child in reception, Year 1 and Year 2, where a meal has been requested.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-02-20T16:42:15.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839306/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839306/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-08","Primary Education: Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the answer of 2 February 2018 to Question 125487, whether local authorities have discretion to not provide a free school meal to a child in (a) reception (b) year 1 and (c) year 2 because of their age.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","127860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839307","Department for International Development","false","2018-02-20","<p>Through CDC, the UK’s Development Finance Institution, DFID has invested a total of $8.8m in Bridge International Academies (BIA) for its global operations in Africa and India. An investment of $1.6m was made in 2016. The remainder was invested in 2013 and 2014. These are long term investments and returnable to the UK taxpayer. In addition, a DFID £3.45m grant, awarded competitively, was also provided to open 23 Bridge academies in Lagos, Nigeria from 2014 through to 2016. This grant is now completed.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2018-02-20T13:47:33.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839307/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839307/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-02-08","Bridge International Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the funds allocated to Bridge International Academies and its parent or subsidiary companies in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","127861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839308","Department for Transport","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Thameslink Programme investment around London Bridge station includes new infrastructure, track and signalling equipment to untangle the tracks. This will provide more capacity through London Bridge station and make train services more resilient.</p><p> </p><p>The new timetable being implemented from May 2018 will take advantage of this investment and will benefit passengers across the south east including on the Thameslink, Southern and Southeastern networks.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail is currently undertaking a review of performance for the new South Eastern franchise.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-02-20T16:45:03.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839308/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/839308/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-02-08","London Bridge Station: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential improvement the performance of Southeastern rail services on completion of the Thameslink project at London Bridge Station; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","127862"
